[src:couchdb/document-oriented-database] A **document-oriented database**, or **document store**, is a computer program and data storage system designed for storing, retrieving, and managing document-oriented information, also known as semi-structured data.
[src:couchdb/document-oriented-database] Document-oriented databases are one of the main categories of NoSQL databases, and the popularity of the term "document-oriented database" has grown alongside the adoption of NoSQL itself.
[src:couchdb/document-oriented-database] XML databases are a subclass of document-oriented databases optimized for XML documents.
[src:couchdb/document-oriented-database] Graph databases are similar, but add another layer, the *relationship*, which allows them to link documents for rapid traversal.
[src:couchdb/document-oriented-database] Document-oriented databases are conceptually an extension of the key–value store, another type of NoSQL database.
[src:couchdb/document-oriented-database] In key-value stores, data is treated as opaque by the database, whereas document-oriented systems exploit the internal structure of documents to extract metadata and optimize storage and queries.
[src:couchdb/document-oriented-database] Although in practice the distinction can be minimal due to modern tooling, document stores are designed to provide a richer programming experience with modern programming techniques.
[src:couchdb/document-oriented-database] Document databases differ significantly from traditional relational databases (RDBs).
[src:couchdb/document-oriented-database] Relational databases store data in predefined tables, often requiring an object to be split across multiple tables.
[src:couchdb/document-oriented-database] In contrast, document databases store all information for a given object in a single document, with each document potentially having a unique structure.
[src:couchdb/document-oriented-database] This design eliminates the need for object-relational mapping when loading data into the database.
[src:couchdb/document-oriented-database] The central concept of a document-oriented database is the notion of a *document*.
[src:couchdb/document-oriented-database] Although implementations vary in their specific definitions, document-oriented databases generally treat documents as self-contained units that encapsulate and encode data in a standardized format.
[src:couchdb/document-oriented-database] Common encoding formats include XML, YAML, JSON, as well as binary representations such as BSON.
[src:couchdb/document-oriented-database] Documents in a document store are equivalent to the programming concept of an object.
[src:couchdb/document-oriented-database] They are not required to adhere to a fixed schema, and documents within the same collection may contain different fields or structures.
[src:couchdb/document-oriented-database] Fields may be optional, and documents of the same logical type may differ in composition.
[src:couchdb/document-oriented-database] The two example documents share some structural elements but also contain unique fields.
[src:couchdb/document-oriented-database] The structure, text, and other data within each document are collectively referred to as the document's content and can be accessed or modified using retrieval or editing operations.
[src:couchdb/document-oriented-database] Unlike relational databases, in which each record contains the same fields and unused fields are left empty, document-oriented databases do not require uniform fields across documents.
[src:couchdb/document-oriented-database] This design allows new information to be added to some documents without affecting the structure of others.
[src:couchdb/document-oriented-database] Document databases often support the storage of additional metadata alongside the document content.
[src:couchdb/document-oriented-database] Such metadata may relate to organizational features, security, indexing, or other implementation-specific features.
[src:couchdb/document-oriented-database] The core operations supported by a document-oriented database for manipulating documents are similar to those in other databases.
[src:couchdb/document-oriented-database] Although terminology is not perfectly standardized, these operations are generally recognized as Create, Read, Update, and Delete (CRUD).
[src:couchdb/document-oriented-database] Documents in a document-oriented database are addressed via a unique identifier.
[src:couchdb/document-oriented-database] This identifier, often a string, URI, or path, can be used to retrieve the document from the database.
[src:couchdb/document-oriented-database] Most document stores maintain an index on the key to optimize retrieval, and in some implementations the key is required when creating or inserting a new document.
[src:couchdb/document-oriented-database] In addition to key-based access, document-oriented databases typically provide an API or query language that enables retrieval based on document content or associated metadata.
[src:couchdb/document-oriented-database] For example, a query may return all documents with a specific field matching a given value.
[src:couchdb/document-oriented-database] The available query features, indexing options, and performance characteristics vary across implementations.
[src:couchdb/document-oriented-database] Document stores differ from key-value stores in that they exploit the internal structure and metadata of stored documents.
[src:couchdb/document-oriented-database] In many key-value stores, values are treated as opaque or "black-box" data, meaning the database system does not interpret their internal structure.
[src:couchdb/document-oriented-database] By contrast, document-oriented databases can classify and interpret document content.
[src:couchdb/document-oriented-database] Document databases typically provide mechanisms for updating or editing the content or metadata of a document.
[src:couchdb/document-oriented-database] Updates may involve replacing the entire document or modifying individual elements or fields within the document.
[src:couchdb/document-oriented-database] These organizational structures may differ between logical and physical representations (e.g. on disk or in memory).
[src:couchdb/document-oriented-database] A document-oriented database can be viewed as a specialized form of key-value store, which is itself a category of NoSQL database.
[src:couchdb/document-oriented-database] In a basic key-value store, the stored value is typically treated as opaque by the database system.
[src:couchdb/document-oriented-database] By contrast, a document-oriented database provides APIs or a query and update language that allows queries and modifications based on the internal structure of the document.
[src:couchdb/document-oriented-database] For users who do not require advanced query, retrieval, or update capabilities, the distinction between document-oriented databases and key-value stores may be minimal.
[src:couchdb/document-oriented-database] Some search engine and information retrieval systems, such as Apache Solr and Elasticsearch, provide document storage and support core document operations.
[src:couchdb/document-oriented-database] As a result, they may meet certain functional definitions of a document-oriented database, although their primary design goals differ.
[src:couchdb/document-oriented-database] In a relational database, data is organized into predefined types represented as tables.
[src:couchdb/document-oriented-database] Each table contains rows (records) with a fixed set of columns (fields), so all records in a table share the same structure.
[src:couchdb/document-oriented-database] Administrators typically define indexes on selected fields to improve query performance.
[src:couchdb/document-oriented-database] A central principle of relational database design is database normalization, in which data that might otherwise be repeated is stored in separate tables and linked using keys.
[src:couchdb/document-oriented-database] When records in different tables are related, a foreign key is used to associate them.
[src:couchdb/document-oriented-database] For example, an address book application may store a contact's name, image, phone numbers, mailing addresses, and email addresses.
[src:couchdb/document-oriented-database] In a normalized relational design, separate tables might be created for contacts, phone numbers, and email addresses.
[src:couchdb/document-oriented-database] The phone number table would include a foreign key referencing the associated contact.
[src:couchdb/document-oriented-database] To reconstruct a complete contact record, the database retrieves related information from each table using the foreign keys and combines it into a single record.
[src:couchdb/document-oriented-database] In contrast, a document-oriented database stores all data related to an object within a single document, and stored in the database as a single entry.
[src:couchdb/document-oriented-database] In the address book example,the contact's name, image, and contact information may be stored together in one document.
[src:couchdb/document-oriented-database] The document is retrieved using a unique key, and all related information is returned together, without needing to look up multiple tables.
[src:couchdb/document-oriented-database] A key difference between the document-oriented and relational models is that the data formats are not predefined in the document case.
[src:couchdb/document-oriented-database] In most cases, any sort of document can be stored in a database, and documents can change in type and form over time.
[src:couchdb/document-oriented-database] For example, a new field such as COUNTRY_FLAG can be added to new documents as they are inserted without affecting existing documents.
[src:couchdb/document-oriented-database] To aid retrieval, document-oriented systems generally allow the administrator to provide hints to the database for locating certain types of information.
[src:couchdb/document-oriented-database] These hints work in a similar fashion to indexes in relational databases.
[src:couchdb/document-oriented-database] Many systems also allow additional metadata outside the content of the document itself, such as tagging entries as part of an address book, which enables retrieval of related information, for instance, all the address book entries.
[src:couchdb/document-oriented-database] This provides functionality similar to a table, but separates the concept (categories of data) from its physical implementation (tables).
[src:couchdb/document-oriented-database] In the traditional normalized relational model, objects in the database are represented as separate rows of data, with no inherent structure beyond what is defined in the tables.
[src:couchdb/document-oriented-database] This can create difficulties when translating programming objects to and from their corresponding database rows, a challenge known as object-relational impedance mismatch.
[src:couchdb/document-oriented-database] In contrast, document stores often map programming objects directly into the database, preserving much of their internal structure.
[src:couchdb/document-oriented-database] Databases using this approach are frequently described as NoSQL systems.
[src:couchdb/document-oriented-database] Most XML databases are document-oriented databases.
[src:couchdb/eventual-consistency] Eventually-consistent services are often classified as providing BASE semantics (basically-available, soft-state, eventual consistency), in contrast to traditional ACID (atomicity, consistency, isolation, durability).
[src:couchdb/eventual-consistency] Eventual consistency faces criticism for adding complexity to distributed software applications.
[src:couchdb/eventual-consistency] This complexity arises because eventual consistency provides only a liveness guarantee (ensuring reads eventually return the same value) without safety guarantees—allowing any intermediate value before convergence.
[src:couchdb/eventual-consistency] Application developers find this challenging because it differs from single-threaded programming, where variables reliably return their assigned values immediately.
[src:couchdb/eventual-consistency] With weak consistency guarantees, developers must carefully consider these limitations, as incorrect assumptions about consistency levels can lead to subtle bugs that only surface during network failures or high concurrency.
[src:couchdb/eventual-consistency] In order to ensure replica convergence, a system must reconcile differences between multiple copies of distributed data.
[src:couchdb/eventual-consistency] The most appropriate approach to reconciliation depends on the application.
[src:couchdb/eventual-consistency] A widespread approach is "last writer wins".
[src:couchdb/eventual-consistency] Another is to invoke a user-specified conflict handler.
[src:couchdb/eventual-consistency] Timestamps and vector clocks are often used to detect concurrency between updates.
[src:couchdb/eventual-consistency] Some people use "first writer wins" in situations where "last writer wins" is unacceptable.
[src:couchdb/eventual-consistency] Whereas eventual consistency is only a liveness guarantee (updates will be observed eventually), **strong eventual consistency** (SEC) adds the safety guarantee that any two nodes that have received the same (unordered) set of updates will be in the same state.
[src:couchdb/eventual-consistency] A common approach to ensure SEC is conflict-free replicated data types.
[src:couchdb/overview] A CouchDB server hosts named databases, which store **documents**.
[src:couchdb/overview] Each document is uniquely named in the database, and CouchDB provides a RESTful HTTP API for reading and updating (add, edit, delete) database documents.
[src:couchdb/overview] Documents are the primary unit of data in CouchDB and consist of any number of fields and attachments.
[src:couchdb/overview] Documents also include metadata that’s maintained by the database system.
[src:couchdb/overview] Document fields are uniquely named and contain values of varying types (text, number, boolean, lists, etc), and there is no set limit to text size or element count.
[src:couchdb/overview] The CouchDB document update model is lockless and optimistic.
[src:couchdb/overview] Document edits are made by client applications loading documents, applying changes, and saving them back to the database.
[src:couchdb/overview] If another client editing the same document saves their changes first, the client gets an edit conflict error on save.
[src:couchdb/overview] To resolve the update conflict, the latest document version can be opened, the edits reapplied and the update tried again.
[src:couchdb/overview] Single document updates (add, edit, delete) are all or nothing, either succeeding entirely or failing completely.
[src:couchdb/overview] The database never contains partially saved or edited documents.
[src:couchdb/overview] The CouchDB file layout and commitment system features all *Atomic Consistent Isolated Durable* (ACID) properties.
[src:couchdb/overview] On-disk, CouchDB never overwrites committed data or associated structures, ensuring the database file is always in a consistent state.
[src:couchdb/overview] This is a “crash-only” design where the CouchDB server does not go through a shut down process, it’s simply terminated.
[src:couchdb/overview] Document updates (add, edit, delete) are serialized, except for binary blobs which are written concurrently.
[src:couchdb/overview] Database readers are never locked out and never have to wait on writers or other readers.
[src:couchdb/overview] Any number of clients can be reading documents without being locked out or interrupted by concurrent updates, even on the same document.
[src:couchdb/overview] CouchDB read operations use a *Multi-Version Concurrency Control* (MVCC) model where each client sees a consistent snapshot of the database from the beginning to the end of the read operation.
[src:couchdb/overview] This means that CouchDB can guarantee transactional semantics on a per-document basis.
[src:couchdb/overview] Documents are indexed in B-trees by their name (DocID) and a Sequence ID.
[src:couchdb/overview] Each update to a database instance generates a new sequential number.
[src:couchdb/overview] Sequence IDs are used later for incrementally finding changes in a database.
[src:couchdb/overview] These B-tree indexes are updated simultaneously when documents are saved or deleted.
[src:couchdb/overview] The index updates always occur at the end of the file (append-only updates).
[src:couchdb/overview] Documents have the advantage of data being already conveniently packaged for storage rather than split out across numerous tables and rows in most database systems.
[src:couchdb/overview] When documents are committed to disk, the document fields and metadata are packed into buffers, sequentially one document after another (helpful later for efficient building of views).
[src:couchdb/overview] When CouchDB documents are updated, all data and associated indexes are flushed to disk and the transactional commit always leaves the database in a completely consistent state.
[src:couchdb/overview] The updated database header is written in two consecutive, identical chunks to make up the first 4k of the file, and then synchronously flushed to disk.
[src:couchdb/overview] In the event of an OS crash or power failure during step 1, the partially flushed updates are simply forgotten on restart.
[src:couchdb/overview] If such a crash happens during step 2 (committing the header), a surviving copy of the previous identical headers will remain, ensuring coherency of all previously committed data.
[src:couchdb/overview] Excepting the header area, consistency checks or fix-ups after a crash or a power failure are never necessary.
[src:couchdb/overview] Wasted space is recovered by occasional compaction.
[src:couchdb/overview] On schedule, or when the database file exceeds a certain amount of wasted space, the compaction process clones all the active data to a new file and then discards the old file.
[src:couchdb/overview] The database remains completely online the entire time and all updates and reads are allowed to complete successfully.
[src:couchdb/overview] The old database file is deleted only when all the data has been copied and all users transitioned to the new file.
[src:couchdb/overview] ACID properties only deal with storage and updates, but we also need the ability to show our data in interesting and useful ways.
[src:couchdb/overview] Unlike SQL databases where data must be carefully decomposed into tables, data in CouchDB is stored in semi-structured documents.
[src:couchdb/overview] CouchDB documents are flexible and each has its own implicit structure, which alleviates the most difficult problems and pitfalls of bi-directionally replicating table schemas and their contained data.
[src:couchdb/overview] But beyond acting as a fancy file server, a simple document model for data storage and sharing is too simple to build real applications on – it simply doesn’t do enough of the things we want and expect.
[src:couchdb/overview] We want to slice and dice and see our data in many different ways.
[src:couchdb/overview] What is needed is a way to filter, organize and report on data that hasn’t been decomposed into tables.
[src:couchdb/overview] To address this problem of adding structure back to unstructured and semi-structured data, CouchDB integrates a view model.
[src:couchdb/overview] Views are the method of aggregating and reporting on the documents in a database, and are built on-demand to aggregate, join and report on database documents.
[src:couchdb/overview] Because views are built dynamically and don’t affect the underlying document, you can have as many different view representations of the same data as you like.
[src:couchdb/overview] View definitions are strictly virtual and only display the documents from the current database instance, making them separate from the data they display and compatible with replication.
[src:couchdb/overview] CouchDB views are defined inside special **design documents** and can replicate across database instances like regular documents, so that not only data replicates in CouchDB, but entire application designs replicate too.
[src:couchdb/overview] Views are defined using JavaScript functions acting as the map part in a map-reduce system.
[src:couchdb/overview] A view function takes a CouchDB document as an argument and then does whatever computation it needs to do to determine the data that is to be made available through the view, if any.
[src:couchdb/overview] It can add multiple rows to the view based on a single document, or it can add no rows at all.
[src:couchdb/overview] Views are a dynamic representation of the actual document contents of a database, and CouchDB makes it easy to create useful views of data.
[src:couchdb/overview] But generating a view of a database with hundreds of thousands or millions of documents is time and resource consuming, it’s not something the system should do from scratch each time.
[src:couchdb/overview] To keep view querying fast, the view engine maintains indexes of its views, and incrementally updates them to reflect changes in the database.
[src:couchdb/overview] CouchDB’s core design is largely optimized around the need for efficient, incremental creation of views and their indexes.
[src:couchdb/overview] Views and their functions are defined inside special “design” documents, and a design document may contain any number of uniquely named view functions.
[src:couchdb/overview] When a user opens a view and its index is automatically updated, all the views in the same design document are indexed as a single group.
[src:couchdb/overview] The view builder uses the database sequence ID to determine if the view group is fully up-to-date with the database.
[src:couchdb/overview] If not, the view engine examines all database documents (in packed sequential order) changed since the last refresh.
[src:couchdb/overview] Documents are read in the order they occur in the disk file, reducing the frequency and cost of disk head seeks.
[src:couchdb/overview] The views can be read and queried simultaneously while also being refreshed.
[src:couchdb/overview] If a client is slowly streaming out the contents of a large view, the same view can be concurrently opened and refreshed for another client without blocking the first client.
[src:couchdb/overview] This is true for any number of simultaneous client readers, who can read and query the view while the index is concurrently being refreshed for other clients without causing problems for the readers.
[src:couchdb/overview] As documents are processed by the view engine through your ‘map’ and ‘reduce’ functions, their previous row values are removed from the view indexes, if they exist.
[src:couchdb/overview] If the document is selected by a view function, the function results are inserted into the view as a new row.
[src:couchdb/overview] When view index changes are written to disk, the updates are always appended at the end of the file, serving to both reduce disk head seek times during disk commits and to ensure crashes and power failures can not cause corruption of indexes.
[src:couchdb/overview] If a crash occurs while updating a view index, the incomplete index updates are simply lost and rebuilt incrementally from its previously committed state.
[src:couchdb/overview] To protect who can read and update documents, CouchDB has a simple reader access and update validation model that can be extended to implement custom security models.
[src:couchdb/overview] CouchDB database instances have administrator accounts.
[src:couchdb/overview] Administrator accounts can create other administrator accounts and update design documents.
[src:couchdb/overview] Design documents are special documents containing view definitions and other special formulas, as well as regular fields and blobs.
[src:couchdb/overview] As documents are written to disk, they can be validated dynamically by JavaScript functions for both security and data validation.
[src:couchdb/overview] When the document passes all the formula validation criteria, the update is allowed to continue.
[src:couchdb/overview] If the validation fails, the update is aborted and the user client gets an error response.
[src:couchdb/overview] Both the user’s credentials and the updated document are given as inputs to the validation formula, and can be used to implement custom security models by validating a user’s permissions to update a document.
[src:couchdb/overview] A basic “author only” update document model is trivial to implement, where document updates are validated to check if the user is listed in an “author” field in the existing document.
[src:couchdb/overview] More dynamic models are also possible, like checking a separate user account profile for permission settings.
[src:couchdb/overview] The update validations are enforced for both live usage and replicated updates, ensuring security and data validation in a shared, distributed system.
[src:couchdb/overview] CouchDB is a peer-based distributed database system.
[src:couchdb/overview] It allows users and servers to access and update the same shared data while disconnected.
[src:couchdb/overview] Those changes can then be replicated bi-directionally later.
[src:couchdb/overview] The CouchDB document storage, view and security models are designed to work together to make true bi-directional replication efficient and reliable.
[src:couchdb/overview] Both documents and designs can replicate, allowing full database applications (including application design, logic and data) to be replicated to laptops for offline use, or replicated to servers in remote offices where slow or unreliable connections make sharing data difficult.
[src:couchdb/overview] At the database level, replication only examines documents updated since the last replication.
[src:couchdb/overview] If replication fails at any step, due to network problems or crash for example, the next replication restarts at the last checkpoint.
[src:couchdb/overview] Partial replicas can be created and maintained.
[src:couchdb/overview] Replication can be filtered by a JavaScript function, so that only particular documents or those meeting specific criteria are replicated.
[src:couchdb/overview] This can allow users to take subsets of a large shared database application offline for their own use, while maintaining normal interaction with the application and that subset of data.
[src:couchdb/overview] Conflict detection and management are key issues for any distributed edit system.
[src:couchdb/overview] The CouchDB storage system treats edit conflicts as a common state, not an exceptional one.
[src:couchdb/overview] The conflict handling model is simple and “non-destructive” while preserving single document semantics and allowing for decentralized conflict resolution.
[src:couchdb/overview] CouchDB allows for any number of conflicting documents to exist simultaneously in the database, with each database instance deterministically deciding which document is the “winner” and which are conflicts.
[src:couchdb/overview] Only the winning document can appear in views, while “losing” conflicts are still accessible and remain in the database until deleted.
[src:couchdb/overview] Because conflict documents are still regular documents, they replicate just like regular documents and are subject to the same security and validation rules.
[src:couchdb/overview] When distributed edit conflicts occur, every database replica sees the same winning revision and each has the opportunity to resolve the conflict.
[src:couchdb/overview] Resolving conflicts can be done manually or, depending on the nature of the data and the conflict, by automated agents.
[src:couchdb/overview] The system makes decentralized conflict resolution possible while maintaining single document database semantics.
[src:couchdb/overview] Conflict management continues to work even if multiple disconnected users or agents attempt to resolve the same conflicts.
[src:couchdb/overview] If resolved conflicts result in more conflicts, the system accommodates them in the same manner, determining the same winner on each machine and maintaining single document semantics.
[src:couchdb/overview] Using just the basic replication model, many traditionally single server database applications can be made distributed with almost no extra work.
[src:couchdb/overview] CouchDB replication is designed to be immediately useful for basic database applications, while also being extendable for more elaborate and full-featured uses.
[src:couchdb/overview] With very little database work, it is possible to build a distributed document management application with granular security and full revision histories.
[src:couchdb/overview] Updates to documents can be implemented to exploit incremental field and blob replication, where replicated updates are nearly as efficient and incremental as the actual edit differences (“diffs”).
[src:couchdb/overview] CouchDB is built on the Erlang OTP platform, a functional, concurrent programming language and development platform.
[src:couchdb/overview] Erlang was developed for real-time telecom applications with an extreme emphasis on reliability and availability.
[src:couchdb/overview] Both in syntax and semantics, Erlang is very different from conventional programming languages like C or Java.
[src:couchdb/overview] Erlang uses lightweight “processes” and message passing for concurrency, it has no shared state threading and all data is immutable.
[src:couchdb/overview] The robust, concurrent nature of Erlang is ideal for a database server.
[src:couchdb/overview] CouchDB is designed for lock-free concurrency, in the conceptual model and the actual Erlang implementation.
[src:couchdb/overview] Reducing bottlenecks and avoiding locks keeps the entire system working predictably under heavy loads.
[src:couchdb/overview] CouchDB can accommodate many clients replicating changes, opening and updating documents, and querying views whose indexes are simultaneously being refreshed for other clients, without needing locks.
[src:couchdb/overview] For higher availability and more concurrent users, CouchDB is designed for “shared nothing” clustering.
[src:couchdb/overview] In a “shared nothing” cluster, each machine is independent and replicates data with its cluster mates, allowing individual server failures with zero downtime.
[src:couchdb/overview] And because consistency scans and fix-ups aren’t needed on restart, if the entire cluster fails – due to a power outage in a datacenter, for example – the entire CouchDB distributed system becomes immediately available after a restart.
[src:couchdb/overview] CouchDB is built from the start with a consistent vision of a distributed document database system.
[src:couchdb/overview] Unlike cumbersome attempts to bolt distributed features on top of the same legacy models and databases, it is the result of careful ground-up design, engineering and integration.
[src:couchdb/overview] The document, view, security and replication models, the special purpose query language, the efficient and robust disk layout and the concurrent and reliable nature of the Erlang platform are all carefully integrated for a reliable and efficient system.
[src:couchdb/replication-intro] One of CouchDB’s strengths is the ability to synchronize two copies of the same database.
[src:couchdb/replication-intro] This enables users to distribute data across several nodes or data centers, but also to move data more closely to clients.
[src:couchdb/replication-intro] Replication involves a source and a destination database, which can be on the same or on different CouchDB instances.
[src:couchdb/replication-intro] The aim of replication is that at the end of the process, all active documents in the source database are also in the destination database and all documents that were deleted in the source database are also deleted in the destination database (if they even existed).
[src:couchdb/replication-intro] There are two different ways to set up a replication.
[src:couchdb/replication-intro] The first one that was introduced into CouchDB leads to a replication that could be called *transient*.
[src:couchdb/replication-intro] Transient means that there are no documents backing up the replication.
[src:couchdb/replication-intro] So after a restart of the CouchDB server the replication will disappear.
[src:couchdb/replication-intro] Later, the _replicator database was introduced, which keeps documents containing your replication parameters.
[src:couchdb/replication-intro] Such a replication can be called *persistent*.
[src:couchdb/replication-intro] Transient replications were kept for backward compatibility.
[src:couchdb/replication-intro] Both replications can have different replication states.
[src:couchdb/replication-intro] A persistent replication is controlled through a document in the _replicator database, where each document describes one replication process (see Replication Settings).
[src:couchdb/replication-intro] For setting up a transient replication the api endpoint /_replicate can be used.
[src:couchdb/replication-intro] A replication is triggered by sending a JSON object either to the `_replicate` endpoint or storing it as a document into the `_replicator` database.
[src:couchdb/replication-intro] If a replication is currently running its status can be inspected through the active tasks API (see /_active_tasks, Replication Status and /_scheduler/jobs).
[src:couchdb/replication-intro] For document based-replications, /_scheduler/docs can be used to get a complete state summary.
[src:couchdb/replication-intro] This API is preferred as it will show the state of the replication document before it becomes a replication job.
[src:couchdb/replication-intro] For transient replications there is no way to query their state when the job is finished.
[src:couchdb/replication-intro] A replication can be stopped by deleting the document, or by updating it with its `cancel` property set to `true`.
[src:couchdb/replication-intro] During replication, CouchDB will compare the source and the destination database to determine which documents differ between the source and the destination database.
[src:couchdb/replication-intro] It does so by following the Changes Feeds on the source and comparing the documents to the destination.
[src:couchdb/replication-intro] Changes are submitted to the destination in batches where they can introduce conflicts.
[src:couchdb/replication-intro] Documents that already exist on the destination in the same revision are not transferred.
[src:couchdb/replication-intro] As the deletion of documents is represented by a new revision, a document deleted on the source will also be deleted on the target.
[src:couchdb/replication-intro] A replication task will finish once it reaches the end of the changes feed.
[src:couchdb/replication-intro] If its `continuous` property is set to true, it will wait for new changes to appear until the task is canceled.
[src:couchdb/replication-intro] Replication tasks also create checkpoint documents on the destination to ensure that a restarted task can continue from where it stopped, for example after it has crashed.
[src:couchdb/replication-intro] When a replication task is initiated on the sending node, it is called *push* replication, if it is initiated by the receiving node, it is called *pull* replication.
[src:couchdb/replication-intro] One replication task will only transfer changes in one direction.
[src:couchdb/replication-intro] To achieve master-master replication, it is possible to set up two replication tasks in opposite direction.
[src:couchdb/replication-intro] When a change is replicated from database A to B by the first task, the second task from B to A will discover that the new change on B already exists in A and will wait for further changes.
[src:couchdb/replication-intro] Local documents are never replicated (see Local (non-replicating) Documents).
[src:couchdb/replication-intro] Selector Objects can be included in a replication document (see Replication Settings).
[src:couchdb/replication-intro] A selector object contains a query expression that is used to test whether a document should be replicated.
[src:couchdb/replication-intro] Filter Functions can be used in a replication (see Replication Settings).
[src:couchdb/replication-intro] The replication task evaluates the filter function for each document in the changes feed.
[src:couchdb/replication-intro] The document is only replicated if the filter returns `true`.
[src:couchdb/replication-intro] Using a selector provides performance benefits when compared with using a Filter Functions.
[src:couchdb/replication-intro] You should use Selector Objects where possible.
[src:couchdb/replication-intro] When using replication filters that depend on the document’s content, deleted documents may pose a problem, since the document passed to the filter will not contain any of the document’s content.
[src:couchdb/replication-intro] This can be resolved by adding a `_deleted:true` field to the document instead of using the DELETE HTTP method, paired with the use of a validate document update handler to ensure the fields required for replication filters are always present.
[src:couchdb/replication-intro] Take note, though, that the deleted document will still contain all of its data (including attachments)!
[src:couchdb/replication-intro] Replication can be especially useful for bringing data closer to clients.
[src:couchdb/replication-intro] PouchDB implements the replication algorithm of CouchDB in JavaScript, making it possible to make data from a CouchDB database available in an offline browser application, and synchronize changes back to CouchDB.
